casts light on patterns and processes that either place groups of older adults at risk of exclusion or are conducive to their inclusion. Leading international experts challenge traditional understandings of exclusion in relation to ageing in From Exclusion to Inclusion in Old Age. They also present new evidence of the interplay between social institutions, policy processes, personal resources and the contexts within which ageing individuals live to show how this shapes inclusion or exclusion in later life. Dealing with topics such as globalisation, age discrimination and human rights, intergenerational relationships, poverty, and migration, the book is essential reading for anyone interested in ageing issues.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aOlder peoplexCare. 0aSocial isolation. 0aSocial work with older people. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Gerontology.2bisacsh1 aAbrams, Dominic, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBarrientos, Armando, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChastonay, Philippe, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCheng, Kevin H.C., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKeating, Norah C, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aKeating, Norah, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLloyd-Sherlock, Peter, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMahmood, Atiya, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMase, Julia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aOgg, Jim, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPhillips, David R., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPhillips, Judith, econtributor.4ctb4h